Why it always returns: for any single `value`, at least one side of `value !== 'a' || value !== 'b'` is true. A value can't be both `'a'` and `'b'` at the same time, so the `||` condition is always satisfied.

Equivalent clearer form:

```js
if (!(value === 'a' || value === 'b')) {
