473.answer:
Direct `===` comparison fails because many decimal values can’t be represented exactly in binary floating point, so results like `0.1 + 0.2` become `0.30000000000000004` instead of exactly `0.3`.

Use an epsilon/tolerance check instead:

```js
const a = 0.1 + 0.2;
const b = 0.3;

const nearlyEqual = (x, y, epsilon = 1e-10) => Math.abs(x - y) < epsilon;

if (nearlyEqual(a, b)) {
  console.log('equal');
}
```

If you only need the inline fix:

```js
if (Math.abs(value1 - value2) < 1e-10) {
  // treat as equal
}
```

For larger-magnitude numbers, a relative tolerance is safer:

```js
const nearlyEqual = (x, y, epsilon = 1e-10) =>
  Math.abs(x - y) <= epsilon * Math.max(1, Math.abs(x), Math.abs(y));
```

