Use `includes()` or `indexOf(...) !== -1` instead of treating `indexOf` as a boolean.

```js
// buggy
if (arr.indexOf(value)) {
  // ...
}

// fixed
if (arr.includes(value)) {
  // ...
}
```

Why it breaks: `indexOf` returns `0` when the item is at the first position, and `0` is falsy, so the condition incorrectly fails there. It also returns `-1` when not found, and `-1` is truthy, so that case can incorrectly pass.

Reliable alternatives:

```js
if (arr.indexOf(value) !== -1) {
  // found
}
```

or

```js
if (arr.includes(value)) {
  // found
}
```

